{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_flobberworm_ver01/data/sn84024927/00414215555/1913062701/0052.xml":{"full_text":"THE ODANAH STAR\nISSUED EVERY FRIDAY.\n\u2018\u2018Entered as second-class matter April 11,\n1913, at the post-office at Odanah, Wis\nconsin, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\u201d\nH. C. ASHMUN, Editor and\nPublisher.\nJ. ASHMUN, Assistant\nEditor.\nODANAH, WIS., FRIDAY, June. 27\nSubscription Rates.\none year $1.50\nsi* months, *75\nFour months, -50\nSpeaking of strikes, they have never\nbeen popular with ball players.\nJqt Coal was once used as money. v lt\nLJs nearly worth its weight in gold to\nday\nNothing but kind words for the hen\nwill do. Fresh eggs are available\ndaily. -T. -i\n\u2019\"i hat n^w;-nickel may serve tb teach\na careless public that a bison is not a\nbuffalo.\nThe.air cocktail, with its oxygen\nflavor, fs thre most invigorating drink\nthese days.\nThe gross debt of the city of Npw\nYork is $1,082,662,851. This Is also a\nnew altitude record.\nThough th\u00a3. new. riickels are In de\nmand; they are still twenty times less\npopular than the old dollar. t\n\u2014i -i i\nCalifornia is to have a \u201cFather\u2019s\nday.\u201d The \u201chead of the house\u201d ia\nnot being forgotten after all.\naverage life of a $lO bill Is a\nlittle-'-more than twelve months.\u201d That\nmap>must live In Philadelphia.\nThe Chicago burglar who robbed the\nsheriff\u2019s office is entitled to a Car\nnegie medal for his high attainment.\nThe English poet, who declared that\nIfe \u2018has supported himself by his\npoetry alone, has attained high am\nbition.\nThe color of hair is due to iron,\nwhich further emphasizes why advice\nfails to enter the brains of many l\npeople*\nThere are* better authorities than a\nHarvard professor to tell us just how\nmany hours of sleep will do us the\nmost good.\nS\nThere will be more money to jingle;\nIn the pockets if the bill for the coin\nage of cents in the United Statesi\ngoes through. _ J\nmBBMk piPji\nKgBB HMH H&reSH WWb\u00dfwb fisgKtls gaawKyH\n_ j\n5 AND 10 CENT STORE\nX-\n\ny and _ v\nOpen Saturday June 28 In Gordon Stan<\nv.,,, ;;j\nWith a Full Line of Up-to-Date Articles ~J\n[Prices that are Right\nHAS worn WILL\nDemocratic Administration De\nservedly Popular.\nWisdom, Firmness and Tact Dis\nplayed by the President Has Sat\nisfied the Voters They Made\nNo Mistake In November.\nThe new administration has now\nbeen in power three months. What\nhas it accomplished, where does it\nstand, and\u2019 what is the outlook for its\nfuture?\nWoodrow Wilson became President\nunder peculiar conditions. He had\nhad only a brief political experience,\nhaving been taken out of the college\ncloister and made governor of New\nJersey as a stepping-stone to higher\nhonors. In that executive position he\nhad shown much capacity, definiteness\nof purpose, and strength of character.\nIt was this fact that led the country\nto accept with confidence his election\nto the presidency, even though he was\nnot the choice of the majority of the\npeople. At the same time, be a\nschoolmaster in politics. Although a\nstudent of government he had not\nbeen active in public life. His ac\nquaintance with men and measures\nwas naturally limited. There was 3till\na doubt in the popular mind whethe\u2019r\nthe fact that he had been a good gov\nernor In his own state insured bis suc\ncessful administration as president.\nWhatever doubts existed upon this\nscore have largely disappeared. Pres\nident Wilson is undoubtedly stronger\nIn the country today than he was\nwhen he entered the White House.\nThis Js due, more than anything else,\nto the fact that he seems to be jra\nbued with good, hard, downright com\nmon sense. This is his most valuable\nasset. lie seems to have the faculty\nof governing his course of conduct by\nrules which insure sensible action. In\npersonal matters, even though he\nshatters precedent, he seems to have\nmet popular approval. Take, \"for in\nstance, his visits to the Capitol and\nhis establishment of an office under\nthe very shadow of the senate cham\nber. It was a bold, unique proceed\ning, but the country has accepted it\nas a wise innovation. In' the treat\nment of international questions, such\nas the Japanese in Cali\nfornia, he has displayed both firmness\nand tact The same characteristics\nare also manifest in his dealings with\nlegislators and legislation. He has\nset himself to accomplish certain re\nsults and does not propose to be dis\nappointed. v\nLimiting Appropriation Bills.\nThe Democratic leaders in the\nhouse have done wisely In ziviz.?\nous consideration to the limitation of\nappropriation bills.\nWhen the late Samuel J. Randall\nmany years ago ran counter in his\nprotection ideas to the free trade pol\nicies of the dominant faction in his\nparty he was punished by the with\ndrawal of appropriation bills from his\ncommittee. Under the new system\nthe bills relating to the army and\nnavy, agriculture, pensions, etc., were\nframed by the committees which dealt\nwith those matters, and, as a natural\nconsequence, each committee, working\nindependently, placed no limit upon\nIts expenditures. It is now proposed\nthat a budget committee shall appor\ntion the amount beyond which no com\nmittee shall go in making up an ap\npropriation bill. Thus there will be\na correlation between the revenues\nand the expenditures and economy\nwill be assured.\nThe effort to rectify \u00a3he abuses of\nthe present system will meet the* com\nmendation of the country anji demon\nstrate the desire of. congress to run\nthe government upon business princi\nples. r\nAppalling Tariff Thought. 4\nThe board of trade of Quincy,\nMass., Says that city will be ruined\nif the duty on finished granite is re\nduced as proposed in the Underwood\nbill.\nReducing the argument to. a syllo\ngism it is: Luxuries should bear a\nhigh duty; tombstones of granite are\na luxury; therefore, the duty on\ngranite tombstones should he kept\nhigh.\nUnless the senate amends the bill\nIt is asserted that \u201cScotch monuments\nwill be seen in our cemeteries.\u201d If\nsenators have, any imagination these\ngrewsome specters surely will be ex\ncluded. v\nDemocratic Success Sure.\nIf the new schedules are effective\nthis summer Vhe country will have a\nyear\u2019s experience upon which to reach\nconclusions next year in ample time\nto line up in the congressional elec\ntions. If Republican predictions about\nbusiness depression have happily\nfailed to materialize In the meantime,\nthe re-election of a Democratic house\nwill be almost a foregone conclusion.\n\n\nProblem for Administration.\nThe gravest problem before tbe ad\nministration is the reduction of the\ncost of living. This is yet to be ac\ncomplished. The Democratic party is\npledged to bring about this result,\nand if it can be successful without\nreducing wages or lessening produc\ntion, it will achieve tremendous popu\nlarity. It is no exaggeration to say\nthat the Democratic leaders view this\nphase of the situation with some anx\niety. The best that they can do is to\nhope for success.\nI\nFrom Facotry to You j\ni When you buy\nWear-U-Well\n\nI I\n\nYou save a DOLLAR or TWO on every J\nI pair of shoes\u2014We are the only from factory\n1 to you shoe makers in the country that cuts\nI out the middle mans prpjfk,and saves you a j\nDOLLAR or TWO\u2014-We have over 600\nfactory branches in America\u2014Our prices are\nI $1.98, $2.48, $2.98 and $3.48 sdme as you -i\npay elsewhere $3.00, $3.50, $4.00 and $5.00\nCall and give us a chance to convince you.\n1\nI t v \"V\" I\n1 A. O. LARSON, Manager\ni\n119-W-2nd~St Ashland, Wisconsin/\nAn aviator in England has made the\nastonishing speed of ninety-four miles\nan hour. Such a flight is enough to\ntake away contemporary breath, to\nsay nothing of the aviator\u2019s.\nThe parcel post has its disagreeable\nfeatures. A collegian recently wrote\nhome for money to purchase socks\nand was stupefied to get them by par\ncel post instead of the usual check.\nA London scientist reports that\nthere is plenty of room yet on earth\nwhich will not be overpopulated for\nten thousand years. This relieves\nmuch apprehension that was felt about\nthe fate of our great-great-great-great\ngrandchildren.\nIn contrast to the tales of factory\ngirls with wages of four and six dol\nlars a week comes the application of\nher guardian for a young girl in New\nYork for an increased allowance, as\nshe cannot possibly live on the pres\nent one of $12,000 a year. After all,\neven necessity in this world of mixed\nthings is a comparative matter.\nCounting the Cost\nOn what you save this Bank allows 3 per cent\nInterest Compounded Semi-annually.\nThe Ashland National Bank\nAshland, Wisconsiu\nA great deal is said about the cost of living, but few\nfamilies or individuals can tell what it cost them to live.\nThey know how much they spend but what portion actu\nally goes for living expenses they do not -know.\nA personal Checking Account at the Bank makes it easy\nto go over the Check Stubs at the end pf the month and\nlearn how much it cost, to live. By this method one\noften finds expenses that can be reduced or avoided en\ntirely and the money saved. We furnish convenient\npocket check books.\nFrank Greene, Proprir","height":"28611","width":"20286"}}
